 {"id":"br-r37-c1-8m1vk","title":"parity: graph_edit_distance family had **kwargs catch-all + timeout raised NotImplemented","description":"Three GED functions (graph_edit_distance, optimize_graph_edit_distance, optimize_edit_paths) exposed only (G1, G2, **kwargs) signatures. inspect.signature() returned a useless catch-all instead of nx's documented per-arg surface. Worse, the timeout kwarg raised NetworkXNotImplemented whenever the native fast path didn't fire, leaving drop-in callers with no way to get a bounded-time result. Aligned all 3 signatures to nx exactly and made the timeout branch delegate to networkx so the iterative algorithm's cutoff actually fires. 10 parity tests freeze the contract.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T04:27:39.988474950Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T04:28:30.381067768Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T04:28:30.379162941Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit ed431ea. graph_edit_distance, optimize_graph_edit_distance, optimize_edit_paths now have explicit per-arg signatures matching nx and the timeout branch delegates to nx instead of raising NetworkXNotImplemented. 10 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-8vobd","title":"parity: approximation TSP family wrappers missing (christofides, greedy_tsp, simulated_annealing/threshold_accepting_tsp, traveling_salesman_problem, asadpour_atsp, metric_closure)","description":"networkx.algorithms.approximation exposes a TSP/metric family that franken_networkx does not: traveling_salesman_problem, christofides, greedy_tsp, simulated_annealing_tsp, threshold_accepting_tsp, asadpour_atsp, metric_closure. All are pure approximation algorithms with no parity-sensitive Rust counterpart in fnx. Add Python wrappers in __init__.py delegating to nx.algorithms.approximation via a new _call_networkx_approximation_for_parity helper (mirrors community/connectivity helpers). Export at top-level and add to __all__. Verify each on a small graph (cycle_graph(5) for TSP, complete_graph(4) for metric_closure).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-25T17:28:04.863008794Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T17:56:54.641577638Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T17:56:54.638612839Z","close_reason":"Shipped in 07416f9: 7 TSP/metric wrappers via _call_networkx_approximation_for_parity helper. Verified greedy_tsp/christofides/traveling_salesman_problem match nx exactly on K4; asadpour_atsp valid on 3-node digraph; sa/ta_tsp produce valid cycles.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-95ayv","title":"parity: voronoi_cells raises NetworkXError instead of ValueError on empty centers","description":"fnx.voronoi_cells(G, set()) raises NetworkXError('center_nodes must not be empty'); nx raises ValueError('sources must not be empty'). Drop-in code catching ValueError to handle empty-centers gracefully fails on fnx (NetworkXError isn't a ValueError subclass). Fix: change to ValueError and align message with nx exactly.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T07:27:52.934359641Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T07:29:25.972596304Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T07:29:25.970740841Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 4c24336. voronoi_cells now raises ValueError with nx's message on empty centers. 6 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-9fa26","title":"parity: core_number dict iterates in sorted-key order, nx iterates in node-insertion order","description":"fnx.core_number returns a dict with keys sorted (e.g. [0,1,2,3,4]) regardless of node-insertion order. nx returns the dict in node-insertion order (e.g. [2,3,0,1,4] when edges were added in (2,3),(0,1),... order). Same iteration-order family as br-r37-c1-pm78h (communicability_betweenness_centrality) and br-r37-c1-f6epo (second_order_centrality). Drop-in code that relies on the iteration order matches nx breaks. Fix: reorder result dict in iteration order of G.nodes().","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:22:48.157628797Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:24:58.180811023Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:24:58.178860072Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit 58e7d6d. core_number now iterates in node-insertion order matching nx. 6 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9m2vs","title":"parity: Graph constructor silently drops edges from dict-of-list adjacency input","description":"fnx.Graph({0: [1], 1: [0, 2], 2: [1]}) returns a graph with 3 nodes and 0 edges. nx.Graph(...) correctly parses it as adjacency-list, returning 3 nodes and 2 edges. _decode_dict_of_dicts_into handles dict-of-DICT shape but skips when the value is a list (continue at 'if not isinstance(nbrs, dict)'). Drop-in code that builds a graph from a dict-of-list adjacency representation gets a wrong graph silently. Same pre-existing pattern from br-r37-c1-lc3em (dict-of-dict input was originally handled, but list-of-neighbours was not). Fix: extend _decode_dict_of_dicts_into to also handle the dict-of-list case (and dict-of-set/tuple by iterating any iterable of neighbour nodes).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T08:48:21.921012966Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T08:53:41.082780910Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T08:53:41.080770904Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit ca5cc1f. Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph/MultiDiGraph constructors now accept dict-of-list (and any iterable-valued dict) adjacency input matching nx.from_dict_of_lists. 11 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9mdsv","title":"parity: label_propagation_communities return type drift","description":"fnx.label_propagation_communities(G) returns dict_values([{0,1,2},...]) — a dict_values view object — while networkx returns a generator yielding sets. Drop-in code that does isinstance(result, types.GeneratorType) or relies on consuming once will diverge. Convert wrapper to yield sets directly (return iter(...)). File: python/franken_networkx/__init__.py (around line 17175).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-25T05:05:05.214287589Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T05:08:52.048798239Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T05:08:52.046958637Z","close_reason":"Invalid: NetworkX 3.6.1 and legacy oracle both return dict_values; existing wrapper and tests already match.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-9yavb","title":"parity: utils.heaps {BinaryHeap, MinHeap, PairingHeap} + classes.function.frozen (4 surfaces)","description":"Two missing utility surfaces: networkx.utils.heaps exposes BinaryHeap, MinHeap, PairingHeap classes used as the default heap= kwarg in stoer_wagner and other algorithms; networkx.classes.function exposes frozen as a no-op exception-raising sentinel attached to frozen graphs by nx.freeze. franken_networkx surfaces neither. Add Python wrappers re-exporting these directly from nx (no graph-conversion needed; they are pure utilities).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-25T23:09:42.538123502Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T23:24:40.588218288Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T23:24:40.586349930Z","close_reason":"Shipped in 63cc1d9: BinaryHeap/MinHeap/PairingHeap re-exports + frozen sentinel. Verified BinaryHeap insert/min/pop, PairingHeap insert/min, frozen() raises NetworkXError as expected.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
